10:56.155 --> 11:01.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Justice in federal court.
Microsoft argues
it's unconstitutional for the
government to

11:02.028 --> 11:08.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ask for customers' personal data
or e-mails
in most cases without the
individuals' knowledge.

11:08.768 --> 11:13.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The company says it's received
more than 5,600
requests for such data from the
government

11:14.040 --> 11:19.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the last year-and-a-half,
often from the
cloud or remote servers. And
nearly half of

11:19.746 --> 11:24.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
those requests come with a ban
from the government
on alerting customers.

11:24.717 --> 11:30.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Brad Smith is the president of
Microsoft.
He joins me from company
headquarters in Redmond,

11:30.490 --> 11:31.357 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Washington.

11:31.457 --> 11:33.326 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And welcome to the program, Brad
Smith.

11:33.426 --> 11:38.431 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I do want to point out we
invited the Department
of Justice to join the
interview, but they

11:38.531 --> 11:40.266 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
declined.

11:40.366 --> 11:43.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, let me begin by asking you,
what is it
that the federal government is
doing that

11:43.536 --> 11:45.405 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Microsoft doesn't like?

11:45.505 --> 11:48.975 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
BRAD SMITH, President,
Microsoft: Well, what
gives us concern is the fact we
have received

11:49.075 --> 11:56.082 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
almost 2,600 -- almost 2,600 of
these so-called
gag or secrecy orders over the
last 18 months.

11:56.182 --> 12:02.989 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Over two-thirds of them have no
end date at
all. So it means that we are
permanently prohibited

12:03.089 --> 12:08.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from telling customers that the
government
has accessed, read and obtained
copies of

12:09.062 --> 12:15.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their e-mails. We feel that
infringes on the
constitutional rights of
consumers and businesses

12:15.768 --> 12:19.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be secure from unreasonable
government
searches.

12:19.138 --> 12:24.944 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It infringes on our First
Amendment right
to speak, to share information
with our customers.

12:25.044 --> 12:29.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, we know the
Justice Department
has not responded to the
lawsuit. They have

12:29.816 --> 12:34.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not said anything publicly, but
we know that
in the past they have said these
are investigations

12:34.754 --> 12:40.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that involve criminals, people
who are breaking
the law, that involve -- that
are perhaps

12:40.994 --> 12:44.597 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
involved in potential terrorist
acts.

12:44.697 --> 12:48.701 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why not work with the government
when they're
trying to go after the bad guys?

12:48.801 --> 12:52.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRAD SMITH: Well, this is an
issue that we
have discussed with various
officials in government

12:53.072 --> 12:54.907 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for some time.

12:55.008 --> 12:59.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we readily recognize that
there are many
cases where there should be some
kind of secrecy,

12:59.779 --> 13:05.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that there is a real danger if
information
is disclosed. But we feel that
these kinds

13:05.685 --> 13:10.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of secrecy orders have been --
become too
routine. They're being issued in
cases that

13:11.024 --> 13:13.993 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
involve businesses, as well as
consumers.

13:14.093 --> 13:20.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it especially concerns us
that there is
no end date. Let's face it.
Forever is a long

13:21.034 --> 13:27.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time. Even military secrets are
declassified
eventually. Why should we have a
country where

13:27.940 --> 13:32.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people will never learn that the
government
has accessed their e-mails?

13:32.612 --> 13:37.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, I was
reading today that
some investigators who have
worked on, I guess,

13:38.017 --> 13:42.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in this area have said that if
you notify
people who are being
investigated, you run

13:42.922 --> 13:46.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the risk that they are going to
change their
communication pattern, they're
going to tamper

13:46.926 --> 13:50.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with evidence. They may even try
to leave
the country. What about that?

13:50.730 --> 13:56.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRAD SMITH: Well, that really
goes to the
point that, yes, there are times
when a nondisclosure

13:56.335 --> 13:59.706 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
order is a sensible thing to do.

13:59.806 --> 14:04.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the law in this case does,
in our view,
not require the government to
make the kind

14:04.711 --> 14:09.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of compelling showing that it
should, and,
hence, the government is getting
these kinds

14:09.649 --> 14:16.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of orders in too many cases. And
even in cases
where this kind of secrecy is
needed, eventually,

14:16.155 --> 14:18.691 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the need for secrecy goes away.

14:18.791 --> 14:23.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And yet, even then, people will
never learn
that the government accessed
their e-mail.

14:23.963 --> 14:29.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that, as much as anything,
really runs,
we think, right into the
constitutional protections

14:29.535 --> 14:31.370 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
we all should enjoy.

14:31.471 --> 14:35.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Brad Smith, what
do you say
to those who look at this and
say, well, this

14:35.808 --> 14:41.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is just an effort to do what's
good for business,
rather than what's good for the
American people,

14:41.614 --> 14:43.483 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for the American government?

14:43.583 --> 14:47.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRAD SMITH: Well, I think this
is fundamentally
about what is good for people
and their rights.

14:48.087 --> 14:53.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is good for technology. It is
good for
businesses who are customers as
well, whose

14:53.893 --> 14:55.628 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
e-mails are being read.

14:55.728 --> 15:00.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, most importantly, I think
it's about
one thing. It's about ensuring
the kinds of

15:00.333 --> 15:07.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
values that we have had in this
country under
the Constitution for 230 years
remain intact

15:07.473 --> 15:13.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
even as technology changes, and
information
that we have long stored on
paper is now stored

15:13.980 --> 15:15.748 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the cloud instead.

15:15.848 --> 15:20.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Did you think
about another
course of action other than
filing suit? Did

15:20.486 --> 15:23.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you try to sit down with the
government and
talk to them about what they're
doing?

15:23.356 --> 15:29.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRAD SMITH: We have had multiple
conversations
about these and similar issues.
And this lawsuit

15:29.996 --> 15:36.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
doesn't for an instant mean that
those kinds
of conversations should come to
an end.

15:36.335 --> 15:42.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I definitely believe that,
ultimately, across
the technology sphere, it's
going to take

15:42.141 --> 15:49.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a lot of good discussion to find
new solutions.
But we have found in recent
cases that things

15:49.348 --> 15:53.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were going the wrong way, not
the right way,
and there does come a point when
you just

15:53.753 --> 15:59.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have to put a stake in the
ground and say
that these constitutional rights
matter, and

15:59.725 --> 16:01.460 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we need the courts to intervene.

16:01.561 --> 16:05.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Is there a middle
ground, though?
Is there some -- something, some
level of

16:05.832 --> 16:10.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
information the government could
share with
you that would make you
comfortable turning

16:10.136 --> 16:14.473 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this individual's e-mails over
to them without
notifying the individual?

16:14.574 --> 16:18.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRAD SMITH: I think we always
have to ask
ourselves at the end of the day,
is there

16:18.611 --> 16:23.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some kind of middle ground that
might emerge?
And I think the answer is
probably yes.

16:23.449 --> 16:29.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If we look at other statutes in
other areas
of federal law, there is
typically a right

16:29.488 --> 16:35.094 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the government in the right
circumstances
to keep something secret for 30
days or 90

16:35.194 --> 16:40.199 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
days, and, if the need
continues, the government
can go back, and it has to make
its case before

16:40.299 --> 16:42.468 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a magistrate yet again.

16:42.568 --> 16:48.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that if we could move
this area of
the law to be more like that
kind of area,

16:48.841 --> 16:50.509 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
we'd find a middle ground
emerge.

16:50.610 --> 16:53.846 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And just finally,
there are
some who are looking at this and
saying, is

16:53.946 --> 17:00.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this some kind of a turning
point in this,
I guess, larger tech industry --
battle with

17:00.786 --> 17:06.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the tech industry -- battle with
the government
on the part of the tech industry
over privacy,

17:06.826 --> 17:09.195 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
over the citizens' privacy?

17:09.295 --> 17:12.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRAD SMITH: Well, I think we're
living in
a time where it feels like there
is a turning

17:12.832 --> 17:14.634 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
point every other month.

17:14.734 --> 17:21.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I step back from it all, I
think what
we're seeing is this evolution
of technology,

17:21.641 --> 17:26.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people storing things digitally,
storing them
in data centers. And across the
board, whether

17:27.046 --> 17:32.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you're in government or you're
in the tech
sector, we're all trying to find
a path, so

17:32.251 --> 17:36.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the traditional values we
have had in
this country, the traditional
rights we have

17:36.555 --> 17:40.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
enjoyed, will remain, so that
information
that's stored in the cloud gets
the same kind

17:40.660 --> 17:43.763 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of protection as information
stored on paper.

17:43.863 --> 17:46.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That, I think, is what we need
to continue
to seek.

17:46.766 --> 17:53.806 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Brad Smith, the
president of
Microsoft, we thank you for
talking with us.

17:53.906 --> 17:59.845 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BRAD SMITH: Thank you.

17:59.946 --> 18:08.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Today, Republican
presidential
front-runner Donald Trump
continued to attack

18:08.220 --> 18:14.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
